The '''Samsung Galaxy S4''' is an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[smartphone]] produced by [[Samsung Electronics]]. First unveiled on March 13, 2013 at Samsung Mobile Unpacked in [[New York City]], it is a successor to the [[Samsung Galaxy S III|Galaxy S III]] which maintains a similar design, but with upgraded hardware and an increased focus on software features that take advantage of its hardware capabilities<U+2014>such as the ability to detect when a finger is hovered over the screen, and expanded [[eye tracking]] functionality (which includes scrolling).<ref name="AndroidcentralSamsungGalaxyS4specs" /><ref name="TechradarSamsungGalaxyS4specs" /> A hardware variant of the S4 also became the first ever smartphone to support the emerging [[LTE Advanced]] mobile network standard.<ref name="s4ltea"/>

The S4 was made available in late April 2013 on 327 carriers in 155 countries.<ref name="ibtimes">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/446284/20130314/samsung-galaxy-s4-launched-new-york.htm |title=Samsung Launches "Slimmer Yet Stronger" Galaxy S4 in New York |last=Gilbert |first=David |date=14 March 2013 |newspaper=[[International Business Times]] |accessdate=15 Mar 2013}}</ref> Upon its release, it became the fastest selling smartphone in Samsung's history; the company sold 20 million S4 units worldwide in the two months following the device's launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_has_reportedly_shipped_20_million_galaxy_s4_units-news-6313.php |title=Samsung has shipped 20 million Galaxy S4 units already |publisher=GSMArena |date= |accessdate=2013-08-28}}</ref>
Samsung has since sold more than 40 million units.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=shm&sid1=105&oid=015&aid=0002968140 |title=<U+AC24><U+B7ED><U+C2DC>S4 <U+D310><U+B9E4> 4000<U+B9CC><U+B300> <U+B118><U+C5C8><U+B2E4>"<U+2026><U+AC24><U+C2A4>3<U+BCF4><U+B2E4> <U+D55C><U+B2EC> <U+BE68><U+B77C>|date=23 October 2013 |newspaper=[[Korea Economic Daily]] |accessdate=23 October 2013 }}</ref>

==Specifications==

===Hardware===
The screen features a {{Convert|5|in|mm|sing=on}} (sometimes stated as 4.99-inch)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://smartphones.techcrunch.com/l/427/Samsung-Galaxy-S4 |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 |author= |date= |work=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> [[PenTile matrix family#PenTile RGBG|PenTile RGBG]] [[Full HD Super AMOLED]] screen with 441&nbsp;pixels per inch and [[Corning Inc.|Corning]] [[Gorilla Glass]] 3.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/galaxys4/lifetask.html |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 |author= |date= |work= |publisher=[[Samsung Electronics]] |accessdate=15 Mar 2013}}</ref> The S4 is widely available in black and white color finishes; in selected regions, Samsung also introduced versions in brown with gold trim, and light pink with gold trim.,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theverge.com/2013/9/25/4769086/samsung-counters-iphone-5s-with-a-golden-galaxy-s4 |title=Samsung counters iPhone 5S with a golden Galaxy S4 |work=The Verge |date= |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref> Purple Mirage and Pink Twilight in Taiwan,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/samsung-galaxy-s4-now-available-in-purple-mirage-and-pink-twilight-colours-in-taiwan-399107|title=Samsung Galaxy S4 Purple Mirage and Pink Twilight|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Red Aurora for AT&T,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.att.com/shop/wireless/devices/samsung/galaxy-s-4-16gb-red-aurora.html#fbid=rp4t7u-J958|title=Samsung Red Aurora|accessdate=July 2013}}</ref> and Artic Blue version by Best Buy<ref>{{cite news |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-19736_7-57611282-251/best-buy-offers-exclusive-blue-samsung-galaxy-s4/|title=Samsung Galaxy S4 Artic Blue Edition|accessdate = November 7, 2013}}</ref>

The S4 comes with either 16&nbsp;GB, 32&nbsp;GB or 64&nbsp;GB of internal storage, which can be supplemented with up to an additional 64&nbsp;GB with a [[microSD]] card slot.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pcpro.co.uk/news/380194/samsung-galaxy-s4-price-specs-release-date-revealed |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 price, specs, release date revealed |last=Collins |first=Barry |date=12 April 2013 |work=[[PC Pro]] |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]] |accessdate=19 Apr 2013}}</ref>

The S4 GT-I9505 includes a multiband LTE transceiver and both models feature an [[Consumer IR|infrared]] LED that can serve as a universal remote control.<ref name="AndroidcentralSamsungGalaxyS4specs" /> On June 24, 2013, a version of the S4 was created in South Korea with support for [[LTE Advanced]] networks. It is the first smartphone ever produced with support for LTE Advanced.<ref name="s4ltea">{{cite news|title=SK Telecom doubles down on LTE|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2969983|accessdate=26 June 2013|newspaper=Korea Joongang Daily}}</ref>  This model includes a quad-core 1.9&nbsp;GHz Krait Snapdragon 800 processor.

Built into the 2600&nbsp;mAh battery is [[near field communication]] (NFC) connectivity, which allows users to perform non-touch payments at shops that employ specially equipped NFC cash registers. The SC-04E model has a [[FeliCa]] secure element, unlike other models which contain an NFC-A secure element. The NFC-A secure element on the SC-04E is provided on the [[Subscriber identity module|SIM card]]. The battery also supports [[wireless charging]] through the [[Qi (inductive power standard)|Qi]] standard except on the SC-04E model.

The S4 supports the [[High Efficiency Video Coding]] (HEVC) video format.<ref name="AndroidcentralSamsungGalaxyS4specs" /><ref name="TechradarSamsungGalaxyS4specs" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/article/456443/samsung_galaxy_s4_has_next-gen_video_codec/ |title=Samsung's Galaxy S4 has a next-gen video codec |last=Simpson |first=Campbell |date=15 March 2013 |work=[[PCWorld]] |publisher=[[IDG]] |accessdate=15 Mar 2013}}</ref>

In addition to the touchscreen, the S4 has several physical user inputs including a home button located near the bottom of the screen, at the bottom of the S4 is the primary microphone and the [[microUSB]] port for both data connections and charging; it also supports [[USB host]] and [[Mobile High-Definition Link|MHL]] 2.0.  There are volume keys on the left side and a power/lock key on the right. At the top there is a {{Convert|0.14|in|mm|sing=on}} headphone jack, the secondary microphone, and [[infrared]] blaster. The backside of the S4 has the 13-megapixel camera and LED flash, and at the bottom left edge has the loudspeaker.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_galaxy_s4-review-914p3.php |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 review: Supernova |author= |date=28 March 2013 |work= |publisher=GSMArena |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>
[[File:Samsung Galaxy S4 Catalonia.jpg|thumb|left|275px|Samsung Galaxy S4 Retail Box with the ''S View Cover'']]

Samsung's official accessory for the S4, the S-View Cover, utilizes a [[hall effect sensor]] in the phone which detects when the cover is closed and displays battery status, time, and other phone statuses in an area of the screen visible through a window on the cover.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theverge.com/2013/3/14/4104134/samsung-announces-galaxy-s4-s-view-cover |title=Galaxy S4's 'S View Cover' shows phone notifications through a cut-out window |first=Adi |last=Robertson |date=14 March 2013 |work=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>

Notably, the S4 does not include an FM radio receiver, as previous models did.<ref>{{cite web 
|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/samsung-explains-why-galaxy-s4-doesnt-come-with-fm-radio-355456
|title=Samsung explains why Galaxy S4 doesn't come with FM radio 
|date=17 April 2013 
|publisher=New Delhi Television 
|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>

The S4 comes in two variants that differ primarily in the internal hardware:

====Quad-core variant====
This S4 version for North America, most of Europe, parts of Asia, and other countries has Qualcomm's [[Snapdragon 600]] SoC containing a quad-core 1.9&nbsp;GHz [[Krait (CPU)|Krait 300]] CPU and an [[Adreno|Adreno 320]] GPU.<ref name="arstechnica">{{cite web |url=http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/03/samsungs-exynos-5-octa-checking-out-the-chip-inside-the-galaxy-s-4/ |title=Samsung<U+2019>s Exynos 5 Octa: Checking out the chip inside the Galaxy S 4 |last=Cunningham |first=Andrew |date=16 March 2013 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]] |accessdate=16 Mar 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qualcomm.com/snapdragon/blog/2013/03/14/samsung-galaxy-s-4-launching-select-regions-snapdragon-600-processors |title=Samsung GALAXY S4 launching in select regions with Snapdragon 600 processors |last=McDonough |first=Tim |date=14 March 2013 |work=Qualcomm Insider Bog |publisher=[[Qualcomm]] |accessdate=16 March 2013}}</ref>

====Octa-core variant====
{{Further|Exynos|Big.little}}
This S4 version has Samsung's [[Exynos|Exynos 5 Octa]] ([[octa-core]]) [[system on a chip]] (SoC) chip containing the first [[ARM Holdings|ARM]] [[Big.little]] [[heterogeneous computing|heterogeneous]] architecture [[central processing unit]] (CPU). The eight core CPU comprises a 1.6&nbsp;GHz [[quad-core]] [[Cortex-A15]] cluster and 1.2&nbsp;GHz quad-core [[ARM Cortex-A7 MPCore|Cortex-A7]] cluster.<ref name="ibtimes" /><ref name="ubergizmo">{{cite web |url=http://www.ubergizmo.com/2013/01/samsung-exynos-5-octa-specs/ |title=Samsung Exynos 5 Octa Specs & Details |last=Nguyen |first=Hubert |date=17 January 2013 |work= |publisher=Ubergizmo |accessdate=16 Mar 2013}}</ref> The cluster of four faster "big" A15 cores is paired with the cluster of four slower, more power-efficient "LITTLE" A7 cores. The chip is capable of running only four cores at a time, either the quad Cortex A15, quad Cortex A7. The switching of the active cluster is performed by a software CPU driver. The CPU emulates a single quad-core processor to the operating system and applications.<ref name="arstechnica" /><ref name="ubergizmo" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arm.com/files/downloads/big_LITTLE_Final_Final.pdf |title=Big.LITTLE Processing with ARM Cortex<U+2122>-A15 & Cortex-A7 |last=Greenhalgh |first=Peter |date=1 September 2011 |work= |publisher=[[ARM Holdings]] |accessdate=17 Mar 2013}}</ref> The SoC also contains an [[Imagination Technologies|IT]] tri-core [[PowerVR]] SGX 544 [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU). The GT-I9500 version of the S4 does not support LTE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://telefoni.com.mk/phone-2851-Samsung-I9500-Galaxy-S-IV.html {{mk icon}} |title=I9500 Galaxy S IV |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Telefoni.com.mk |accessdate=25 Apr 2013}}</ref> The E300K/L/S versions support LTE, with the Cortex-A15 also clocked at 1.6&nbsp;GHz.<ref name="SHV-E300KDS3KC-spec" /><ref name="SHV-E300LDS3LC-spec" /><ref name="SHV-E300SDS3SC-spec" />

===Software===
{{Further|Android (operating system)|TouchWiz|S Voice}}
[[File:Galaxy S4 with TouchWiz.png|thumb|left|160px|S4 using TouchWiz]]
The S4 ships with Android 4.2.2 and Samsung's [[TouchWiz|TouchWiz Nature]] user experience. [[Eye tracking]] features have been extended on the S4; the new "Smart Scroll" feature can be used to scroll while looking at the screen by slightly tilting the phone, and "Smart Pause" allows the video player to pause videos if the user is not looking at the screen. "Air View" implements gestures and other functionality (such as previewing images or messages) by holding or swiping a hand or finger slightly above the screen, similar to the "S-Pen" features utilized on Samsung's Galaxy Note series. The "Group Play" feature allows [[ad hoc]] sharing of files between Galaxy phones, along with multiplayer games and music streaming between S4 phones. The S4 also introduces [[Samsung Knox|Knox]], a suite of features which implements a sandbox for enterprise environments that can co-exist with a user's "personal" data. Knox also incorporates use of the ARM [[TrustZone]] extensions and security enhancements to the Android platform.<ref name=engadget-knoxoverview>{{cite web|title=Samsung announces SAFE with Knox, details plans to secure the enterprise Galaxy (hands-on)|url=http://www.engadget.com/2013/02/25/samsung-safe-with-knox/|work=Engadget|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>

The camera app implements numerous new features (some of which were first seen on the [[Samsung Galaxy Camera|Galaxy Camera]]), including an updated interface, and new modes such as "Drama" (which composes a moving element from multiple shots into a single photo), "Eraser" (which takes multiple shots and allows the user to remove unnecessary elements from a picture), "Dual Shot" (which uses the front-facing camera for a [[picture-in-picture]] effect), "Sound and Shot" (which allows the user to record a voice clip alongside a photo), "Animated Photo", and "Story Album" among others. Other new pre-loaded apps include WatchOn (an [[electronic program guide]] that can utilize an infrared transmitter on the top of the phone as a TV remote), S Translator, the workout tracker S Health, [[S Voice]] Drive, S Memo, [[TripAdvisor]], and an [[optical character recognition]] app.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/samsung-galaxy-s4/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 keeps calm, carries on with big screen, 8-core chip and, yes, eye tracking |last=Dolcourt |first=Jessica |date=14 March 2003 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=19 Apr 2013}}</ref>

====Updates====
Between June<U+2013>July 2013, Samsung began rolling out an update to the firmware; the update allows apps to be moved to the SD card, freed 80 megabytes of space, adds stability to the camera, and adds a new feature that increases legibility on the display.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/update-rolling-out-for-atts-galaxy-s4-241248/ |title=Update rolling out for AT&T's Galaxy S4 |publisher=Androidauthority.com |date=2013-07-09 |accessdate=2013-08-28}}</ref>  For the S4 variants on AT&T and Verizon, this update removed the ability to apply the previous bootloader exploit known as "Loki".

In early August 2013, the Google Play Edition variant of the S4 began to receive an update to [[Android 4.3]]. In November 2013, Samsung released the Android 4.3 update to most variants of the S4.

To prevent [[grey market]] reselling, models of the S4 manufactured after July 2013 implement a [[regional lockout]] system in certain regions, requiring that the first [[SIM card]] used on a European and North American model be from a carrier in that region. Samsung stated that the lock would be removed once a local SIM card is used.<ref name=verge-samsunglock>{{cite web|title=Samsung region locking the Note 3 to keep out resellers|url=http://www.theverge.com/2013/9/26/4772820/samsung-region-locks-european-galaxy-note-3-within-europe|work=The Verge|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>

{{clear}}

===Model variants===
Several different model variants of the S4 are sold, with most variants differing only in support for regional network types and bands.

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;font-size:85%;"
|-
