====Google Play Edition====
At the [[Google I/O]] 2013 keynote, Samsung and Google revealed that an edition of the U.S. S4 would be released on June 26, 2013 through [[Google Play]], featuring stock Android 4.2.2, later updated to 4.3, with Samsung provided updates;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/06/26/google-no-factory-image-or-driver-binary-hosting-for-google-play-edition-one-or-s4-oems-will-handle-otas/ |title=Google: No Factory Image Or Proprietary Binary Hosting For Google Play Edition One Or S4, OEMs Will Handle OTAs |last=Ruddock |first=David |date=26 June 2013 |work=Android Police |publisher=Illogical Robot LLC |accessdate=30 June 2013}}</ref> it has an unlockable bootloader (similar to [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices) and supports LTE on AT&T and T-Mobile's networks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theverge.com/2013/5/15/4333716/galaxy-s4-stock-android-google-io-2013 |title=Google turns the Samsung Galaxy S4 into a Nexus phone, coming June 26th for $649 |last=Hollister |first=Sean |date=15 May 2013 |work=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref> The model number is GT-I9505G.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/smartphones/samsung-galaxy-s4-google/4505-6452_7-35761621.html |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 Google Play Edition review: Powerhouse Android gets elegantly purified |last=La |first=Lynn |date=26 June 2013 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=30 June 2013}}</ref>

====Verizon Developer Edition====

A Developer Edition of the 16 GB S4 in black was released for users on [[Verizon Wireless|Verizon]], exclusively from Samsung's website on June 25, 2013. This variant ships with an unlocked [[bootloader]], which can be used for the development and installation of custom ROMs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Verizon Dev Edition|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/06/25/verizon-samsung-galaxy-s4-developer-edition-now-available-for-650/|work=Android Police|accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref>

====LTE Advanced====
Samsung released a refreshed S4 in South Korea with the model numbers SHV-E330K/S/L in August 2013 that are the same as previous models, except it has a Qualcomm [[Snapdragon 800]] and [[LTE Advanced]] support that allows the phone to download data at up to 150 Mbit/s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gadgetmania.com/2013/08/samsung-galaxy-s4-lte-advanced-the-refreshed-s4-is-pushing-the-limits-on-both-data-and-processing-speed/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 LTE-Advanced <U+2013> the refreshed S4 is pushing the limits on both data and processing speed|author= Gadgetmania |publisher= Gadgetmania.com |accessdate=Sep 2013}}</ref> Model SHV-E330L for [[LG Uplus]] is world's first "100% LTE" smartphone that can utilize data, voice and text over LTE only. The phone does not use LG Uplus 3G CDMA network;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsma.com/membership/lg-uplus-the-first-in-the-world-to-commercialize-the-100-lte-system-the-releasing-of-100-lte-smart-mobile-phone-galaxy-s4-lte-a|title=LG Uplus, the first in the world to commercialize the <U+2018>100% LTE<U+2019> system <U+2013> The releasing of 100% LTE smart mobile phone <U+2018>Galaxy S4 LTE-A<U+2019>|date=2013-07-18|accessdate=2013-09-25}}</ref> however, when used outside Korea the phone has to fall back to using GSM and UMTS networks as LG Uplus is the only carrier that can support LTE-only mode and this caused confusion among consumers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metroseoul.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=237858 |title=LG U+, 100% LTE |publisher=Metroseoul.co.kr |date= |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref>

Samsung also plans to release an LTE-A model for [[Deutsche Telekom]] later this year.

====Samsung Galaxy S4 for LTE in Rural America====
Samsung released model SCH-I545L in support of [[Verizon Wireless#LRA|LTE in Rural America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/09/10/mysterious-verizon-galaxy-s4-variant-sch-i545l-turns-out-to-be-for-rural-lte-partners/|title=Galaxy S4 Variant (SCH-I545L) Isn't A Limited Edition Or LTE-A Device, Turns Out To Be For Rural LTE Partners|date=2013-09-10|accessdate=2013-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/cell-phones/SCH-I545ZWALRA|title=Samsung Galaxy S4 (Generic)|accessdate=2013-09-27}}</ref>

==Reception==

===Critical reception===
The S4 received mostly positive reviews. GigaOM's Tofel says he would recommend the S4 "without hesitation" and says that it's "Samsung's defining phone".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gigaom.com/2013/04/23/samsung-galaxy-s-4-review/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S 4 reviewed: Too many features or just right? |last=Tofel |first=Kevin C. |date=23 April 2013 |work= |publisher=[[GigaOM]] |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref> ReadWrite's Rowinski described the phone as a "solid smartphone," but criticised Samsung's use of "[[bloatware]], pre-loaded apps and features that you will likely never use," but called the S4 "a first-rate smartphone."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://readwrite.com/2013/04/23/samsung-galaxy-s4-more-less-review |title=Samsung Galaxy S4: Sometimes, More Is Less [Review&#93; |last=Rowiski |first=Dan |date=23 April 2013 |work=[[ReadWrite]] |publisher=[[SAY Media]] |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref> Time's McCraken says the S4 is a smartphone with everything, it has the biggest screen and the most built-in features. He wishes the S4 marks the end of Samsung's plan to just add too many new features with its flagship smartphones.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://techland.time.com/2013/04/24/samsung-galaxy-s4-review/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S 4 Review: Gimme One Smartphone, with Everything |last=McCracken |first=Harry |date=24 April 2013 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time Tech]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>

Technology journalist [[Walt Mossberg]] described the S4 as "a good phone, just not a great one". Mossberg wrote "while I admire some of its features, overall, it isn<U+2019>t a game-changer." Mossberg criticized the software as "especially weak" and "often gimmicky, duplicative of standard Android apps, or, in some cases, only intermittently functional." He urged readers to "consider the more polished-looking, and quite capable, [[HTC One]], rather than defaulting to the latest Samsung."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20130423/galaxy-s-4-is-a-good-but-not-a-great-step-up |title=Galaxy S 4 Is a Good, but Not a Great, Step Up |last=Mossberg |first=Walt |date=23 April 2013 |publisher=[[AllThingsD]]}}</ref>

''[[Consumer Reports]]'' named the S4 as the top smartphone as of May 2013 due to its screen quality, multitasking support, and built-in IR blaster.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/05/20/tech/mobile/galaxy-s4-top-smartphone |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 named top smartphone by Consumer Reports |last=Kelly |first=Heather |date=21 May 2013 |work=[[CNN|CNN Tech]] |publisher=CNN |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>

Despite only using about 1 GB more than the S III, critics noted that about half of the internal storage on the S4's 16 GB model was taken up by its system software; leaving only 8 to 9.15 GB for the storage of downloaded apps (some of which cannot be moved to the SD card) and other data. Samsung initially stated that the space was required for the S4's new features, but following a report regarding the issue on the [[BBC]] series ''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog]]'', Samsung stated that it would review the possibility of optimising the S4's operating system to use less local drive space in a future update.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crave.cnet.co.uk/mobiles/samsung-defends-16gb-s4s-mere-8gb-of-usable-storage-50011111/ |title=Samsung defends 16GB S4's mere 8GB of usable storage |last=Westaway |first=Luke |date=2 May 2013 |work=[[CNET|CNET UK]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/phone-and-communications/mobile-phones/samsung-promises-to-review-galaxy-s4-storage-space-after-watchdog-expos--1151872 |title=Samsung promises to review Galaxy S4 storage space after Watchdog expos<U+00E9> |last=Solomon |first=Kate |date=16 May 2013 |work=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcadvisor.co.uk/news/mobile-phone/3444658/samsung-galaxy-s4-storage-woes/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 suffers from storage woes |last=Martin |first=Chris |date=29 April 2013 |work=[[PC Advisor]] |publisher=[[IDG]] |accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> Storage optimizations were brought in an update first released in June 2013, which frees 80 MB of internal storage, and restores the ability to move apps to the device's SD card.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theverge.com/2013/6/6/4401652/samsung-galaxy-s4-update-storage-improvements-sd-card-apps |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 update addresses storage complaints with move to SD card feature |last=Souppouris |first=Aaron |date=6 June 2013 |work=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>

===Commercial reception===
The S4 reached 10 million pre-orders from retailers in the first two weeks after its announcement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thetechstuff.com/3024/samsung-galaxy-s4-is-already-hit-with-10-million-pre-orders-two-weeks |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 is already a hit with 10 million pre-orders in two weeks |last=Jones |first=Luke |work= |publisher=The Tech Stuff |accessdate=19 Apr 2013}}</ref> In the United States, this prompted Samsung to announce that due to larger than expected demand, the roll out of devices on U.S. carriers Sprint and T-Mobile would be slower than expected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/apr/25/samsung-galaxy-s4-launch-date |title=S4 launch date delays |author= |date= |work= |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 Apr 2013}}</ref>

The S4 sold 4 million in 4 days and 10 million in 27 days making it the fastest selling smartphone in Samsung's history and the fastest selling Android device in history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/phone-and-communications/mobile-phones/samsung-galaxy-s4-already-hits-6-million-sales-1151486 |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 already hits 6 million sales |last=Davies |first=Chris |date=15 May 2013 |work=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-23/samsung-galaxy-s4-sales-hit-10-million-in-half-the-time-of-s3.html |title=Samsung Galaxy S4 Sales Hit 10 Million in Half the Time of S3 |last=Culpan |first=Tim |date=23 May 2013 |work= |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref> The [[Samsung Galaxy S III]] sold 4 million units in 21 days, the [[Samsung Galaxy S II]] took 55 days and the [[Samsung Galaxy S]] took 85 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashgear.com/samsung-ships-4m-galaxy-s-4-in-4-days-breaks-internal-record-15282061/ |title=Samsung ships 4m Galaxy S 4 in 4 days: Breaks internal record |last=Solomon |first=Kate |date=15 May 2013 |work=[[SlashGear]] |publisher=R3 Media LLC |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>

Samsung shipped more than 20 million S4 smartphones by June 30, which is around 1.7 times faster than the Galaxy S III.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.techstake.org/2013/07/samsung-sold-20-million-galaxy-s4-units.html |title= Samsung Already Shipped 20 Million plus Galaxy S4 Units Worldwide, |author= Aditya Dey |publisher= techstake.org |accessdate=July 2013}}</ref>
As of October 23, 2013, Samsung has sold over 40 million S4 units six months after release.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moon |first=Mariella |url=http://www.engadget.com/2013/10/24/samsung-galaxy-s4-sales-40-million/ |title=Samsung sold over 40 million Galaxy S 4s in six months |publisher=Engadget.com |date=2013-04-27 |accessdate=2013-10-25}}</ref>

==Battery problems and safety issues==
A house in [[Hong Kong]] is alleged to have been set on fire by an S4 in July 2013,<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/29/galaxy-s4-fire-explosion_n_3672346.html Exploding Samsung Galaxy S4 Allegedly Starts Fire, Destroys House]</ref> followed by a minor burnt S4 in [[Pakistan]].<ref>[http://axeetech.com/2013/08/13/another-samsung-galaxy-s4-found-burned-at-the-bottom-during-charging/#.UhM7WBa2BTA Another Samsung Galaxy S4 found burned at the bottom during charging]</ref> A minor fire was also reported in [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[United Kingdom]] in October 2013.<ref>[http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/10725415.___Exploding_phone____sets_pram_on_fire/?ref=mr Exploding phone sets pram on fire]</ref> Some users of the phone have also reported swelling batteries and overheating;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/Samsung-acknowledges-Galaxy-S4-swelling-battery-issue-offers-free-replacements_id48352 |title=Samsung acknowledges Galaxy S4 swelling battery issue, offers free replacements |last=P. |first=Daniel |date=16 October 2013 |work=PhoneArena |publisher=PhoneArena |accessdate=25 November 2013}}</ref> Samsung has offered customers affected new batteries free of charge.<ref>[http://en.kioskea.net/news/24175-samsung-launches-galaxy-s4-battery-trade-in-program Samsung Launches Galaxy S4 Battery Trade-In Program]</ref>

===Richard Wygand===
On December 2, 2013, Canadian resident Richard Wygand uploaded a YouTube video describing his phone combusting and acknowledged the product being defective.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wygand|first=Richard|title=samsung galaxy s4 caught fire proof for samsung|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dc4duKuPrQ0|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> The phone was plugged into AC power overnight; he woke up to the smell of smoke and burning matter. In the video, the power cord was shown to be severely burnt and warped. damage to the power plug.

Later in the video, Wygand describes how he attempted to get a replacement.
{{quote|We have a service provider; it<U+2019>s [[Rogers Wireless|Rogers]] here in Canada. Rogers [has] seen it, and they freaked out. They even said, <U+2018>You could send it in through us <U+2014> it<U+2019>ll take three weeks <U+2014> or just go see Samsung.' The Samsung reps just said that they need video proof, and now we have to call it in. So we<U+2019>re gonna upload this, send it to Samsung. We<U+2019>ll let you know how it goes.}}

In his second video, uploaded a few days after the first one, Wygand states that in order to receive a replacement phone, Samsung allegedly asked him to sign a legal document requiring him to remove the video, remain silent about the agreement, and surrender any future claims against the company.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wygand|first=Richard|title=et tu, samsung? (Legal document received from Samsung)|url=http://pastebin.com/D3G2iKDP|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wygand|first=Richard|title=samsung galaxy s4 catches on fire samsung wants silence|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?annotation_id=annotation_3703862793&feature=iv&src_vid=dc4duKuPrQ0&v=2QHd-_qncEU|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> It is unknown whether or not he signed the document, but his frustrations has been expressed in his video. In an interview with [[Mashable]], Wygand said that since he posted the second video, no further response from Samsung was received.<ref>{{cite web|last=Strange|first=Adario|title=Galaxy S4 Customer Posts Defective Phone Video, Samsung Demands Removal|url=http://mashable.com/2013/12/10/samsung-s4-burns-up-user-posts-video-samsung-ask-him-to-remove-it/|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> However, an official spokesman from Samsung told Mashable, <U+201C>Samsung takes the safety and security of our customers very seriously. Our Samsung Canada team is in touch with the customer, and is investigating the issue.<U+201D>

